## Now Let's Configure It

### Step 1 — Place Your Files
Put both files in your working directory:
```
C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\
    ├── worker.properties
    ├── mongodb-sink.properties
    ├── truststore.jks
    ├── keystore.jks
    ├── your-keytab.keytab        ← add here
    └── cert.pem                  ← add here
```

---

### Step 2 — Import PEM into a Truststore

Your `cert.pem` is the MongoDB server's CA certificate. Java can't read PEM directly — we need to import it into a JKS truststore using Java's `keytool`.

Run this in Command Prompt:
```cmd
"C:\Program Files\Java\jdk-17.0.2\bin\keytool.exe" -importcert -trustcacerts -file C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\cert.pem -keystore C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\mongo-truststore.jks -storepass changeit -alias mongoCA -noprompt
```

This creates a new `mongo-truststore.jks` file that Java can use to trust your MongoDB server.

---

### Step 3 — Create a JAAS Config File

JAAS (Java Authentication and Authorization Service) is how Java talks to Kerberos. Create a new file:

`C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\jaas.conf`

```
com.sun.security.jgss.krb5.initiate {
    com.sun.security.auth.module.Krb5LoginModule required
    useKeyTab=true
    keyTab="C:/Users/G01516271/kafka-connect-test/your-keytab.keytab"
    principal="YOUR_KERBEROS_PRINCIPAL"
    storeKey=true
    isInitiator=true;
};
```

> ⚠️ Replace `YOUR_KERBEROS_PRINCIPAL` — this is the Kerberos identity tied to your keytab. Ask your MongoDB/infra team:
> "What is the Kerberos principal associated with our keytab file?"
> It looks something like `mongodb/hostname@DOMAIN.COM`

---

### Step 4 — Update `mongodb-sink.properties`

Change your connection URI:
```properties
connection.uri=mongodb://user@glodsr02z02401.intranet.barcapint.com:27181/?authMechanism=GSSAPI&authSource=$external&tls=true&tlsCAFile=C:/Users/G01516271/kafka-connect-test/cert.pem
```

Key changes:
- `authMechanism=PLAIN` → `authMechanism=GSSAPI`
- Added `tlsCAFile` pointing to your PEM
- Removed `tlsInsecure=true` — no longer needed since we have the real cert now ✅

---

### Step 5 — Update Startup Command

Add the JAAS config to your startup:
```cmd
set KAFKA_OPTS=-Djavax.net.ssl.trustStoreType=WINDOWS-ROOT -Djava.security.auth.login.config=C:\Users\G01516271\kafka-connect-test\jaas.conf

set KAFKA_HEAP_OPTS=-Xms256m -Xmx1g

bsp\opt\kafka_2.13-2.8.0\bin\windows\connect-standalone.bat kafka-connect-test\worker.properties kafka-connect-test\mongodb-sink.properties
```

---

## Summary of What Each Piece Does

| Piece | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `cert.pem` → `mongo-truststore.jks` | Java trusts MongoDB's SSL certificate |
| `jaas.conf` | Tells Java how to use keytab for Kerberos |
| `keytab file` | Proves your identity to MongoDB without a password |
| `authMechanism=GSSAPI` | Tells MongoDB driver to use Kerberos |

---

## Before You Do All This

Get the **Kerberos principal** from your infra team — without that the `jaas.conf` won't work.

